ToDo 9

Add these lines to the script file of the previous section. Try to find out, either by experiment- ing or by using the help, what the meaning is of rgb, the last argument of rgb, lwd, pch, cex.

thirdscript

#contents of thirdscript.R
x1<-rnorm(100)
x2<-rnorm(100)
x3<-rnorm(100)

t<- data.frame(a=x1, b=x1+x2, c=x1+x2+x3)

#added lines
plot(t$a, type="l", ylim=range(t),
     lwd=3, col=rgb(0.9,0,0,0.9))
lines(t$b, type="s", lwd=2,
      col=rgb(0,0.9,0,0.9))
points(t$c, pch=4, cex=1,
       col=rgb(0,0,1,0.9))

Meanings of Graphical Parameters

rgb = Red, Green, Blue and Alpha Colour Specification where alpha is the opacity of the color.

lwd = Line width relevant to default = 1.

pch = Specify symbol for plot points.

cex = The number that the plot text and symbols should be scaled to. 1 = default, 0.5 = 50% of default, 1.5 = 150% of default.

Todo 13

Make a vector from 1 to 100. Make a for-loop which runs through the whole vector. Multiply the elements which are smaller than 5 and larger than 90 with 10 and the other elements with 0.1.

e <- seq(from=1, to=100, by=1)
k <- c()
for(i in 1:100)
{
  if (e[i]<5)
  {
    k[i]=e[i]*10;
  }
  else if (e[i]>90)
  {
    k[i]=e[i]*10;
  }
  else
  {
    k[i]=e[i]*0.1;
  }
}

Todo 14

Write a function for the previous ToDo, so that you can feed it any vector you like (as argument). Use a for-loop in the function to do the computation with each element. Use the standard R function length in the specification of the counter.

x = function(arg1)
   {
     len = length(arg1)
     for(i in 1:len)
       {
         if (arg1[i] < 5)
           {
             arg1[i] = arg1[i] * 5;
             }
         else if (arg1[i] > 90)
           {
             arg1[i] = arg1[i] * 10;
             }
         else
           {
             arg1[i] = arg1[i] * 0.1;
             }
         }
     return (arg1)
}
x(arg1 = 60)

Todo 15

The ToDo above (ToDo 14) can be done more easily and quickly without a for-loop but with regular vector computations.

y = function(arg1)
   {
     if (arg1 < 5)
       {
         arg1 = arg1 * 5;
         }
     else if (arg1 > 90)
       {
         arg1 = arg1 * 10;
         }
     else
       {
         arg1 = arg1 * 0.1;
         }
     return (arg1)
}
y(arg1 = 91)
